{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Traveling-salesman heuristic route length is <= 1.5x optimal for up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure boundary is the heuristic algorithm quality itself (route construction + length calculation), which can be exercised in-process with deterministic coordinate fixtures. No I/O or external dependency is required to expose a real regression.","test_description":"Call the heuristic directly with a corpus of fixed coordinate sets (small sets with exact optimal baseline, larger sets with trusted precomputed-optimal baselines), compute ratio heuristic/optimal, and fail if any case exceeds 1.5. This catches real algorithm regressions (e.g., bad neighbor selection, swap bug) without needing API/network wiring.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Delivery time window estimates are correct from segment distance and configured average speed by road type.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on interaction between distance/segment data and speed-configuration lookup by road type. Boundary bugs (wrong key, fallback speed, unit mismatch across modules) often appear only when modules are wired together.","test_description":"Run estimator through its real module wiring: provide a multi-segment route with mixed road types and a real config object/source used in production wiring, then assert per-segment and total time windows match expected distance/speed math (including unit conversion). This detects cross-module mapping/config defects that a single-function test could miss.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Shift-hours validator rejects routes exceeding remaining shift hours and returns excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a local validation rule (compare total estimated time vs remaining shift, compute overage). Real failures are arithmetic/threshold logic bugs within one object/function boundary.","test_description":"Invoke validator with representative totals around the boundary (equal, just under, just over, large overrun) and assert rejection flag plus exact excess value. This catches real off-by-one/rounding/sign errors without any external wiring.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If one address fails geocoding (no results), service skips it, optimizes remaining stops, and reports skipped addresses.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is at module boundaries: geocode-result handling, filtering, optimizer input construction, and skipped-address reporting. A single-function unit test would miss orchestration defects.","test_description":"Exercise the service orchestrator with a stub geocoding client that returns coordinates for most addresses and no-results for one. Assert the failed address is recorded as skipped, omitted from optimizer input, and the returned route covers only successfully geocoded stops. This catches real pipeline interaction failures without requiring live HTTP.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate input addresses are consolidated into one stop with combined delivery items and not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Correctness spans deduplication/aggregation plus downstream routing behavior (single visit). Boundary issues can occur when normalization, merge logic, and optimizer inputs are connected.","test_description":"Run the service with repeated addresses carrying distinct delivery items, then assert output contains one consolidated stop with merged items and route visits that location once. This exposes real integration bugs where dedupe appears correct in isolation but duplicates reappear in route planning.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.69,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
